Below is a concise breakdown of how the target scene is built and exactly which dictionary blocks (in their given orientations) match each piece. Finally, a sample step‐by‐step assembly order is provided.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1)  ANALYSIS OF THE MAIN TARGET IMAGE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
•  There are two separate structures.

LEFT STRUCTURE (3 layers, 4 total blocks)  
  – Bottom Layer: Two red arches side by side.  
  – Middle Layer: One green rectangular block bridging across the two arches.  
  – Top Layer: One red block that appears rectangular from the front (actually an arch turned so its curved gap is hidden from this view).  

RIGHT STRUCTURE (4 layers, 6 total blocks)  
  – Bottom Layer: Two tall green “columns” standing vertically.  
  – Second Layer: One wide yellow rectangular block bridging across the columns.  
  – Third Layer: One red arch placed front‐facing so the arch is visible.  
  – Top Layer: Two orange triangular wedges forming a peaked roof.

Overall block count: 10.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2)  SELECTING THE REQUIRED DICTIONARY BLOCKS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Below are the matches (no re‐orienting allowed—must use the blocks exactly as shown):

•  Red arch blocks with the arch facing front‐to‐back → Dictionary index 2  
   – Used 3 times total (two for the left structure’s bottom, one for the right structure’s third layer).  

•  Tall red “rectangular” top on the left (actually an arch turned sideways) → Dictionary index 5  
   – Used once (left structure top).  

•  Horizontal green block (left middle) → Dictionary index 6  
   – Used once.  

•  Tall green pillars (right bottom) → Dictionary index 8  
   – Used twice.  

•  Wide yellow bridging block (right second layer) → Dictionary index 13  
   – Used once.  

•  Two orange triangular wedges for the roof → Dictionary indices 15 and 16  
   – Used once each.  

Block‐Index List and Usage Summary  
  – #2  (red arch) × 3  
  – #5  (red arch, sideways) × 1  
  – #6  (green rectangle) × 1  
  – #8  (tall green rectangle) × 2  
  – #13 (wide yellow rectangle) × 1  
  – #15 (orange wedge) × 1  
  – #16 (orange wedge) × 1  

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3)  STEP‐BY‐STEP ASSEMBLY ORDER
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Below is one possible sequence. You may of course group them differently, but each step simply places one block:

{
  "Step1": "Move block with index 2",
  "Step2": "Move block with index 2",
  "Step3": "Move block with index 6",
  "Step4": "Move block with index 5",
  "Step5": "Move block with index 8",
  "Step6": "Move block with index 8",
  "Step7": "Move block with index 13",
  "Step8": "Move block with index 2",
  "Step9": "Move block with index 15",
  "Step10": "Move block with index 16"
}

This completes the left stack first (Steps 1–4) and then the right structure (Steps 5–10).
